gov.nasa.larcfm.Util

Class ParameterData

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.nasa.larcfm.Util.ParameterData

  • public class ParameterData
extends java.lang.Object
    This class stores a database of parameters. In addition, it performs various operations parameter strings, including parsing some more complicated parameter strings into various data structures.

    All key accesses are case insensitive, however the actual key values are stored with case information intact. Methods returning the key values (getList, getListFull) will reflect the capitalization scheme used for the initial assignment to a key.

This is intended to create a unique ParameterData object representing the parameters of a particular instance (of many) of an object, that can then be collected along with others into a larger ParameterData object representing the containing object.

      • extractPrefix

        public ParameterData extractPrefix(java.lang.String prefix)
        Return a copy of this ParameterData, with the string prefix removed from the beginning of all key values. If any key value in this object does not start with the given prefix, do not include it in the returned object. This is intended to filter out the parameters of a particular instance of a group of objects. The resulting ParameterData object will include an empty string parameter if a key exactly matches the prefix.

      • setPreserveUnits

        public void setPreserveUnits(boolean v)
        If true, then all subsequent calls to "set.." methods will not update the units in the database to the units supplied through a "set.." method. The only exception is if the units in the database are "unspecified" then the units in the database will be updated with the value of units supplied through a "set.." method.
        Parameters:
        v - true when the units in the database should be preserved

      • isUnitCompatibility

        public boolean isUnitCompatibility()
        Will set methods disallow updating a unit if the new unit is incompatible with the old unit. Meters and feet are compatible, whereas meters and kilograms are not. Most of the time, one wants the enforcement that compatible units are required, but there may be some situations where this is undesired.
        Returns:
        true, if set methods must use compatible units with the units in the database

Most of the time, one wants the enforcement that compatible units are required, but there may be some situations where this is undesired.
        Parameters:
        v - true when the units in a set method must be compatible with the database.

      • set

        public boolean set(java.lang.String s)
        Parses the given string as a parameter assignment. If successful, returns a true value and adds the parameter. Otherwise returns a false value and makes no change to the parameter database. If the supplied units are unspecified, then the units in the database are used to interpret the value given.

        Examples of valid strings include:

        • a = true
        • b = hello everyone!
        • c = 10 [NM]
        Parameters:
        s - the given string to parse
        Returns:
        true if the database was updated, false otherwise. The database may not be updated because of an invalid parameter string was given, or incompatible units, etc.

      • set

        public boolean set(java.lang.String key,
                   java.lang.String value)
        Associates a parameter key with a value (both represented as strings). The value field may include a units descriptor in addition to the actual value, usually in a format similar to '10 [NM]', representing 10 nautical miles. If the supplied units are unspecified, then the units in the database are used to interpret the value given.
        Returns:
        true if the database was updated, false otherwise. The database may not be updated because of an invalid parameter string was given, or incompatible units, etc.

      • parseArguments

        public java.util.List<java.lang.String> parseArguments(java.lang.String prefix,
                                                       java.lang.String[] args)
        Parses the array of strings as if they were command line arguments and puts them into this ParameterData object.

        The prefix is the command line parameter designator. For instance, if the command line argument is "-Px=10mm" then the command line designator is "-P" and the parameter is "x=10mm", that is, the parameter name "x" will be added with a value of 10 millimeters. Any arguments that do not begin with the command line designator are not included in this ParameterData object and are instead returned, in order. In other words, this strips the array of strings of recognized parameters and stores them, and returns the rest in a list.

        Parameters:
        prefix - command line parameter designator
        args - the command line arguments
        Returns:
        the command line arguments that do not begin with the designator
